Name: Kāpiti Coast
Speaker_1: Te Aputa ki Wairua Parata Kauri

Name: Palmerston North
Notes: By whakapapa, the best person to say these names would have been a descendent of Chief Te Awe Awe, and a daughter of his was insistant that it should be so, but none of his children spoke the language. (In fact Te Awe Awe had lived a double life, going by an English name and playing in a jazz band.) Eventually she relented, and Matawhā "Pompey" Durie, father of Judge Eddie and Dr Mason Durie, said them, and he was amply qualified to do so.

Name: Waiōuru/Raetihi
Notes: Mr Mareikura was very frail when I recorded him, and died soon after. I went to the aftermath of his tangi, and secured the permission of his family to use the recording nonetheless.

Name: Tūrangi/South Taupō
Notes: Before I recorded any Taupō names, I consulted Sir Hepi Te Heu Heu, who took me to morning tea in Taumarunui. He very modestly declined to speak, but recommended those who did, each of whom was excellent.

Name: Marton
Notes: I have often played this track to illustrate the beauty of the Māori language and its placenames.

Name: Taumarunui
Notes: I had very much hoped to record the voice of Titi Tihu for the upper Wʰanganui river. I tracked him down, driving along the centre of the road towards Tawataʰa. Aged in his 90s, he spoke only Māori, and my reo was not up to the task explaining my mission and talking him into speaking. The names were instead spoken by his nephew in something of a hurry, in a room overlooking a busy Taumarunui street (perhaps they aren't usually, but this one was).

Name: Waverley
Notes: Ruka Broughton (Sr) was ideally qualified to say the names of this region, which closely corresponds to the rohe of his people Ngā Rauru (Kītahi), "Ngā Rauru of the Single Word". Only in the east was there an issue. Some names close to the Wʰanganui river might have belonged to the people of the river. At Ruka's direction, I went back to the Wʰanganui elders and was told, no, they belong to Ngā Rauru. Ruka said "I knew they did, but I wanted them to say it." - a beautiful example of Māori diplomacy, one of many I experienced in my travels.

Name: Murupara
Speaker_1: John Henry Bird, QSO in Apa-hapai-taketake
Notes: About 30 seconds into this track, at Kiorenui, a fly goes around the microphones. People listening on headphones often try to swat it away.

Name: Mangakino
Speaker_1: Major Meihana in Tamatea Pokai Whenua

Name: Maungatautari

Name: Inner Gulf Islands

Name: Auckland Isthmus (Ancient)
Notes: Auckland has a rich vein of historial names that are no longer current, or have been modified over time. Thus it became useful to divide it into "ancient" (to approximately the mid-19th century) and "modern".

Name: North Shore

Name: Islands off Bream Head

Name: The Far North
Speaker_2: Merimeri Penfold in Tane Nui a Rangi

Name: Addenda

Name: Chatham Islands (Ancient)
Notes: The "ancient" list is intended to be of Moriori names. They are spoken by Charles Solomon, son of the last "full-blooded" Moriori. He did not, however speak the Moriori language.

Name: Chatham Islands (Modern)
Notes: The "modern" list is of current Māori names, dating from 1835.
